title: New Spring Loaded Bowden Extruder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a new original Bowden extruder. My goal was to enclose the filament path and maintain its alignment as you increase/decrease spring tension or lift it off the extruder gear.

Parts:
1 M5 thread bowden tube fitting
1 608ZZ bearing
1 bangood bed leveling spring (20mm L, 7.5mm OD)
1 M5 x 30mm button head screw
3 M3 x 10mm button head screws
1 M3 x 20mm button head screw (see note below)

Note:

  1. Use the 20mm screw as the tension arm pivot. On my stepper a 20mm screw bottoms out tight with the tension arm held tightly to the stepper mount. However it can still pivot freely. This may vary with different motors and screws. Go to a shorter or longer screw and trim it if necessary to get the right fit.

  2. Drill out the filament path with a sharp 5/64" or 2mm drill bit to ensure the diameter is perfect and to clear any filament that may have drooped into the path. Use very low RPM if you go fast it will get hot, melt the PLA and make a mess.

I have printed this, it all fits and works as designed. See pics above...enjoy!

title: Anet A8 top frame brace | Anti Z wobble
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Most frame braces try to stabilize the z-axis by reinforcing the acrylic parts among each other. If you already placed your printer in a solid enclosure, you have the perfect opportunity to easily eliminate all motion induced by motion on the x-axis completely.

Like many others, my printer is installed in an IKEA Lack housing, so it is designed to fit this height (50 cm). However, i added elongated holes, so it can be used for heights from 49.5 cm to 50.5 cm (i have an anti-slip mat under my printer, so that works, too).

The struts are mounted between the acrylic top frame and the display board, replacing the stock plastic spacers. The preferred way to install it is with the flat side to the back, so you have easy access to the screws on the upper side. The files are named [L] and [R] respectively.

Some pros:

  • The struts don’t restrict your print area
  • It won't budge. I even have to wall-mount my table to keep the printer from moving it (showing how bad the A8 needs reinforcements)
  • It's a simple print. You won't use a lot material and it should print in less than 2 hours (each)
  • It's compatible with most other mods. I haven't seen too many using the display screw holes - mostly spool holders, which are out of the question anyway when using enclosures

Some cons:

  • It's fixed in height. I'm working on a customizable / adjustable version

Important note: This design is intended for the 5 button display. It won’t fit the jog dial version.

FYI
The photos show an early version when i just wanted to check dimensions with some excess medium quality filament - the struts are different and not filleted... will update anytime soon. In the meantime: feel invited to print and test it for yourself.

author: BenGarvis

description.text:
This is a replacement turn signal indicator mount for a 2012 Triumph Tiger 800 motorcycle. The OEM parts are made of a poor hard rubber compound and can break without any damage to the indicator lights themselves, requiring that you purchase the entire assembly for ~ $50 US. This mount fits and looks like factory when installed. You need to remove the original torn rubber making sure to get it all out of the light housing, then the tube on this replacement goes in with a nice friction fit. You can use a little glue if you want to keep it from turning and getting misaligned. The part is made ABS and the stalk tube is thin walled... and I included a necked down section that in the event of impact should fail without doing damage to the bike's plastic side panel. This part saved me a lot of $ and kept me from having to wait for an OEM replacement. Enjoy.

Edit: Being relatively new to 3D printing I made this part out of ABS since it is supposed to be stronger and more environmentally durable than other materials. But I discovered that 3D printed ABS parts don't have very high adhesion between layers. Since this part is best printed flat side of the mount down it comes out with many potential failure planes when bending moment is applied. I found that as designed and printed in ABS the part is really too fragile taking only a minor bump to break it. So I am going to try printing replacements in PLA and also PET-G materials. I recommend you consider the same. I also may revise the wall thicknesses if necessary.

Edit 2: redesigned with a notch in the mount tube to clear and index on the tab on the clear lens cover and to make part just a little stronger.

Edit 3: I broke 2 more of my replacements on the rear left of the bike in my tiny garage parking the bike and walking by with luggage. Ugghhh. So, here is an alternative modular design to give near OEM flexibility. Print the both "2Piece" files and press in a 38mm length of hose. I am using hard rubber washing machine hose sized 10mm ID and 15mm OD. The 15mm OD makes a nice press fit into the printed parts. Then the 17mm OD of the printed end part makes a nice press fit into the light housing. I need to print one in black next time I reload filament. Use some super or hybrid super glue to keep the tube from coming out when the signal inevitably gets bumped.

description.text:
I needed a bunch of picture frames, and have a 3D printer.  What else could I do?   
Have a picture or photograph or sign that needs hanging? Now you can 3D print a picture frame to fit it exactly, even if it's larger than your 3D printer's print bed.  
Check out the 'remixes' to see sizes that are already generated. Or Customize to fit your picture!

Open in Customizer and enter the picture's dimensions, and the size of the screw. You can enter either inches or mm, but not both. Note that for pictures to snap into the frame, they either need to be fairly stiff or be held in place by a cover sheet. The screw needs to be counter-sunk, and the right type for the wall. That is, a drywall screw, concrete screw, wood screw, etc. If you want to protect the pictures, you can use clear plastic sheet, cut to match the pictures. For example: http://www.amazon.com/Polycarbonate-Sheet-Transparent-Thickness-Length/dp/B000FP83P4/ref=pd_sim_sbs_op_3?ie=UTF8&refRID=0SCB23X8HSNNHS6CSGCY. The print all of the parts in the plate, or individually:
  • Center
  • (2x) Left Arm
  • (2x) Right Arm
    • Drill a hole in the wall where you want the center of the picture. The hole should be smaller than the screw, so it serves as a guide but leaves material for the threads to grip. Put the screw through the center, and screw it into the guide hole, leaving it loose . Fit the four arms around the center, so they form an X. The center's four connectors will snap down into the arms. There's a picture showing how the arms fit onto the center. Rotate the frame to the desired orientation, and tighten the screw down. Put the picture, and cover if desired, into the frame. You'll have to bend it slightly to fit into the frame's corners, then press it flat and it will snap into place. Admire your art!

This was designed using Adobe Illustrator to trace out the original logo using paths and then saving that as an SVG. Next I imported the SVG into Fusion 360 and extruded the profiles

A Moineau pump based paste extruder.
suited for printing different pastes. The moineau design has been tested with chocolat. For this model: wax, ceramic clay and moldable plastic will be possible aswell. for the actual printing of chocolate a double walled part/module will be prefered to allow heating of the parts. (or use a resistance wire with an attached temperature controler)

Edit: the rotor and Oldham-Midle will be re-dimensiond to allow a smoother functioning when printed with a lower resolution. This paste extruder printhead is inspired on the Moineau extruder thingy from Ttsalo and redesigned for use with other pastes than chocolate.
(where cleansing with boiling water is not possible) It is a modular design so feel free to edit any module to adjust these to the paste you want to use it for. and will save costs if a part needs to be replaced due to wear & tear, or due to an unsuccesfull cleaning of a used paste. Especially the stuts and mountbase will require an other design for fitting on different printers: the mounting points on the inlet part are intended to be used for different adapters (in this case studs) to allow the fitting on different printers. The parts are printed using a Dimension 1200ES, which allow for small spacings between the rotor and stator 0,245mm. printers with a lower accuracy may need a larger spacing. For the assembly 35 M3x10 bolts are needed with M3 nuts.
(the same as are used for attaching the Stepper engine. The insert is designed to allow the material to be pushed in with the aid of a plunger. If u use the Repman based foot a threaded rod is required to use for the action of the z-axis switch (the foot is made as the standard bolt tends to miss the z axis on rare occasions causing problems. As you might notice the stepper-motorshaft hole has a flatened edge.
this is done as the axis of our stepper engine has a side filed of to increase grip and avoid the snapping of a clamped part design. THe use of pressurized air is not (yet) possible: the printed parts tend to be semi-permeable and let water and air run through "solid" walls.
a surface coating or impregnation could solve this problem but has not yet been tested. .ipt parts will be added later to ease re-design and creation of additonal modules. The O-ring grooves are designed for 22mm x 2.5 mm O rings but near similar sizes can be used aswell.

title: Roomba Furniture Bumper
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The iRobot Roomba is great because it's compact design allows it to fit under a lot of furniture to get a thorough clean, however due to the fact that I have a strip of LED lights underneath my media center (a IKEA Besta set), the Roomba tends to find it's way underneath to rip my light strip out.

Thus the bumper - essentially it is designed to act as a physical obstacle that the Roomba can hit which protects my LED strip or anything else you don't want to get damaged. I have the bumper surface extended with a back and forth accordion style spring to help absorb the impact. I attached the bumper with two strips of 3M adhesive tape (see pictures). Time will tell if this is sufficient to keep the bumper attached to the furniture.

I will probably add a small cutout adhesive foam pad to the front of the bumper so the plastic doesn't scratch or do damage to the robot.

Thanks for checking out my thing. If you have any ideas to make it better, feel free to leave a comment or remix!

description.text:
If you own a CNC mill without automatic end stops, you've probably had to restart a few jobs from the beginning because you over-ran where your end stops would've been, or you did something that set off your CNC mill's alarm. This optical alignment tool will help you get back on track from where you made your mistake rather than forcing you to start over by allowing you to manually re-zero your CNC using a cheap USB microscope you can mount to your CNC mill.

Parts Needed:

  • A 12mm diameter USB microscope. I bought this one for another project a while ago. and share it between that other project and this. You may be able to adapt this part to fit other microscope designs, but although the above-linked product is no longer available, there are, at present, several other identical microscopes available on Amazon:
    • https://www.amazon.com/Koolertorn-Microscope-Adjustable-Collections-Inspection/dp/B01FZ0FNA6/ref=sr_1_21?s=electronics&ie=UTF8&qid=1504669228&sr=1-21&keywords=USB+microscope
    • https://www.amazon.com/Microscope-MixMart-Endoscope-Collections-Inspection/dp/B01L6L80Q2/ref=sr_1_35?s=electronics&ie=UTF8&qid=1504669280&sr=1-35&keywords=USB+microscope
    • https://www.amazon.com/Microscope-1600x1200HD-Endoscope-Collections-Inspection/dp/B06XHHJ1SS/ref=sr_1_39?s=electronics&ie=UTF8&qid=1504669280&sr=1-39&keywords=USB+microscope
    • https://www.amazon.com/Andonstar-10-300x-Microscope-ImagingOptical-resolution/dp/B071WK7QCC/ref=sr_1_63?s=electronics&ie=UTF8&qid=1504669298&sr=1-63&keywords=USB+microscope
  • (Optional) 2x M5 Roll-in spring T-nuts. These are used for securing your target in a stable position. They are not strictly necessary -- the part might be snug enough in its design to not be too-easily moved, but if you do not use these, I recommend holding the target arm in place using a little bit of tape. If you do go the spring t-nut route, you probably don't need to screw them in using a bolt as you've seen me do in the above photos; the spring is probably more than enough tension to prevent anything from moving around.
  • Software allowing you render crosshairs on your webcam's image. This is something that both bCNC and Chilipeppr can do with minimal effort.

After printing the target arm, you will want to either draw a target onto the top of the arm, or print, cut out and tape or glue on a gridded target like I've done.

Use Instructions:

  1. Before beginning your print job, zero your CNC such that your camera's crosshairs are exactly aligned with the target image.
  2. Machine your thing. If a problem occurs causing your CNC to become un-zero'd, move your CNC back to the zero position by moving to the point at which your camera's crosshairs line up with the target image as they did in step #1.

description.text:
###################### NEW Version 2 ######################

  1. Fittings are 50% small1er reducing fillement used, and improving the over all look of the push rods.
  2. The sections of 16 gauge wire used for the connection to control arms and horns has been reduced.
  3. No more Z bends. The adapter now has a built in keaper arm that allows the use of a simple 90deg bend in the wire, while making installation and removal easier.

###########################################################

Parts [Makes 1 push rod]:
A. 2 skewer pushrod fittings.
B. one bamboo skewer around 3.1mm - 3.2mm dia.
C. About 60mm of 16 gauge wire.
D. Glue. Use CA glue, I am specifically using Gorrilla super glue, and having excellent results with pla. I had some issues with a few other name brands while testing. Note: Hot glue did work well in testing as long as the parts were a snug fit to begin with. Use with caution.

To assemble:

  1. Bend about 3mm at the end of the wire 90 degrees.
  2. Cut the wire exactly 25mm back from the L bend. See photo above ^
  3. Insert the first L wire into the smaller opening on the fitting, and the blunt end of the skewer into the larger opening.
  4. If they fit well, reinstall with a drop of glue on each.
  5. Connect the first end to your servo and mark the skewer where the control arm hole is.
  6. Cut the skewer exactly 25mm back from the mark.
  7. Repeat steps 1 through 4 for the second end.

Thats it, It's really simple, I just over explained the steps a little.

Comment if you test this, and let me know how it turned out for you.

Note: I model knowing the limitations of my 3D printer. Its old and has a few minor quirks. In general its accurate but holes especially tend to print out smaller than they are sized in the model. As such I model holes slightly larger to accommodate this. Test print any part and make sure any attached hardware like wire or skewers fit properly before bulk printing.

description.text:
So, I'm just going to say it. This is a stupid thing. You really shouldn't even consider building this. If there was a downvote button, this would be where you'd click it and hateful, hurtful comments are semi-justified. If you feel compelled to try and make me cry, I'll understand.

That said, this is one of my favorite designs. It came together well, looks decent, and I'm overall very happy with how it turned out. Done again, I'd try and make it smaller, but again, it's a stupid idea so I won't do it again.

The original idea was to build an Amazon Echo for my garage at half the cost using an Amazon Dot and a cheap $20 Bluetooth speaker called the Urge Basics Cuatro. If Amazon Echo's still cost $200, I would feel much better about how this turned out. Unfortunately, around the time I ordered my dot, the echo's started dropping in price. First they went to $99, and a few days ago I just saw one for less than $75. At that price, you really can't beat the quality and price (the rumor is that a nextgen version of the echo is right around the corner).

I originally planned on breaking the Cuatro speaker down and trying to build a smaller, custom enclosure for the internal parts. This would have left me with a much smaller overall size, but upon disassembly, it became obvious that this was going to be way trickier than I expected because of the passive radiator. Without that particular feature, the speakers sounded horribly anemic so I ended up just enclosing the entire speaker.

I power mine with a cheap 5v internal PSU. I just as easily could have used a USB Y connector, but I ordered a bunch of these for arduino projects and wanted to avoid needing a wall-wart.

So just to drive home how stupid this thing is. Here's the breakdown.

Design time: roughly 10 hours.
Print time: 20+ hours (the first prototype failed).
Filament cost: probably $5 to $10 bucks
Electronic (Dot/Speaker/PSU): $70
Amazon Echo cost: $75 shipped

Test your 7.3L Powerstoke UVCH wiring with ease. Unplug the UVCH harness at the valve cover and plug this in to get a convenient test point / break-out-box. Box dimensions are 110mm x 80mm x ~45mm.

Instead of using a store bought ABS project box and drilling holes, I modeled and printed one based one that I already had used for something else and added the lettering and holes.

Install the grommet before you fish your wires through and BEFORE you crimp your terminals on.

description.text:
Did you even wonder why it takes so long unscrew the build vat hold downs on the D7? Is it designed to take an extra deep vat? I doubt it. I bet that's just the length of screws they had at the factory. But because of this sub-optimal set up it takes extra time unscrewing the knobs every time you pull the build vat. You could replace the offending screws with something of a more convenient length but that is difficult because the right hand screw can't be removed without removing the power supply (on a v1.4 at least). I came up with this quick fix which doesn't require you to buy anything or make permanent alterations to your printer.

Print two of the spacers on your D7.
Open the front of the case.
Unscrew the vat hold down knobs.
Back out the hold down screws until the spacers fit.
Slide the spacers in place and tighten the screws against the spacers.
Close up the case and you are done.

Note that the ideal spacer would be a few mm longer but the right hand screw runs into the power supply which limits how much we can lower that screw. In the interests of symmetry I made the left match.

description.text:
This is a simple adapter piece to fit a 12-mm steel ball or 14-mm glass ball into a 22-mm diameter slot.

Many of the fidget spinner models utilize 608-2RS ball bearing as a weight around the center. With the help of this simple adapter you can quickly fit steel or glass balls to various fidget spinner models you can find.

kuula-adapteri_12mm_to_22mm_R1p5mm.STL

The outer diameter is smaller in the first model. Print some of both types and you'll always have some adapters that fit your newly-found spinner model.

kuula-adapteri_14mm_to_22mm_MEDIUM.STL
kuula-adapteri_14mm_to_22mm_SMALL.STL

These models are probably less usable because glass balls are various sizes. My balls were roughly 14 mm in diameter. I ended up using 3 different color-coded models so that I always could can find the adapter that fits a certain glass ball.

description.text:
This is a customizable wall mount hook set for displaying swords... or whatever you want to hang from hooks, I guess :) The way this is designed, the hook slides up behind the back plate. A screw is used to anchor both of these to the wall through the mounting hole. This is designed to accommodate #6 screw anchors. Then to cover the screw, a face plate is slid down over the back plate.

So far, I have only made two face plates - one with my signature hot pepper design, and the other with a calligraphic letter 'T', for Tombrello. I have included a blank plate for you to make your own design. If there is enough interest, I might be willing to do all of the letters of the alphabet myself.

There are two hooks. The smaller hook works well for swords with little to no protrusion of the hilt. My particular swords have a rather large diameter hilt, so I had to move them away from the wall a bit.

Pay no attention to the unfinished wall in the photos. That was the previous occupants "handiwork." I'll get around to repairing that later.

title: Mod X Carriage with Stock Head and Adjustable Sensor Mount

description.text:
Well, I've been trying to collect all the right parts to upgrade the spider, but as I'm printing and learning, and finding my limitations, I discovered that there aren't quite the exact upgrades that I Now believe I need to make. I'm new to printing, just over a month, and I;ve been thinking and reading of other new Makers needs and experiences also. Having been an Industrial CNC tech, I know the need for adjustability, functionality, adjustability, serviceability, Ect, did I mention Adjustability?.....
So I am working on New Tarantula Owners Upgrades. Sounds better than stuff newbies can print, right? My idea is to be able to print upgrades easily. no supports, EZ bridging, modular, functional, and with this one in particular I wanted to be able to see my nozzle printing. I've learned a lot from watching prints grow. Slightly faster than grass, so that's kool, but people do think your a bit loony for staring at a machine making weird noises...
So with the Bla Bla out of the way, I took a bunch of other guys stuff cause I thought it was really kool and tweaked it out a bit, threw it into 123design, spunit around a bit and this stuff came out.
I used the Tevo Tarantula Modular X w/ BLTouch by montymintypie, https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2007048 as a start, I really think the belt locks are great, and as this is for new owners, not newbs, like me, I made this for stock equipment. So I filled in the BL mount and added the drag chain mount from Maxdarkdog, https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2396718
I remixed the chain mount to have Backstops for the chain so it doesn't droop and .25mm supports under the bridging section, they break out and clean up REAL ez. even when I'm dialed in and bridging nicely, the supports keep it real clean. And i've had layer adhesion issues due to rough spots in dodgy bridging. So, it has micro supports. I can't stand the way slicers generate supports anyway.
Next we have the Modular X stock head from Thingirob, https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1438795
To which was added a parametric slide mount from Ken_Applications
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2015855
And designed to hold the Green stock sensor.
The sensor is minutely adjustable by the turn of an allen wrench. Makes that first layer ez to get right.
Also I threw in half of the Fan Duct by Juangv
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:236813 It's cut in half because the sensor is on the other side.
In was having a problem with the belt locks teeth not coming out right in the slicers no matter what I did, I dunno. So, I scaled them in Slic3r to 105%, and shortened them a little in 123design. You can see in the Pics the 105% scaled part fits the teeth in the belt perfectly, but just didn't sit right, as you can see the new ones sit tight. Yes, one is shorter than the other because it's under the drag chain. If it;s in anyone's way, let me know and I'll shorten it up a bit more for ya. The slide and carrier are meant to print upright, all this should be able to print flat, no supports, and if your still playing with settings it should still be workable. the slide and carrier are Very tight. it;s on purpose, the layer lines will bind it up. having to work it gently makes it smooth. don't overwork it, you want it smooth, not sloppy.
It;s not perfect, please let me know if you have problems with it. And for those New to 3D Printing owners of a Tarantula, stay tuned I've made Maxdarkdog's XYZ chain easier for us to print too, as soon as I get the files organized I'll post it. Thanks all Hope you can use it,
I will be!
I also added a complete set, minus fan duct, With a cooling tower. I will help keep the dimensions on the tall skinny pieces.

UPDATE: Had a problem with the fan duct sagging at ABS bed temps.By the second layer.So, I beefed it up, it might not be elegant, but it seems to be working. i'm printing business card puzzles. It's been right on top of the bed for 45min, and it;s solid. Already replaced the file. Happy Printing!

I use lots of perimeter layers, 8 or so. makes it strong on all the mounting holes. 4-5 top and bottom layers. Mines Really rigid and strong.
3mm x 12-20mm to mount the slide, the holes go all the way through you won;t bottom out.
the adjustment screw is 3mm x 35mm.The Sensor mounts with 3mm x 16mm. I had the spring laying around, definitely put one in!
the mod head mounts with 4mm x 15mm screws. Locknuts recommended.
Got it installed. Much better view now.

description.text:
I created this because I want to get a laser and I would like to attach other items to my Delta printer.

Delta push rod arm separation spacing = 42mm
Hot End = E3D V5 , (I am not sure if it will fit the V6 "Probably Not").

I am currently testing it on my Micromake D1 and it is working really well for me.
I have made some changes after my print and this is still untested but should improve the overall design.

There is no Offset on the parts so you will have to clean it up to fit. I prefer it this way it makes for a solid part when assembled.

All the holes can be tapped or enlarged that will be up to you.

You only need some M3 Nuts and Bolts long and short.

For the AirDirectAddon you will need some 15mm M3 bolts with small heads so it does not hit the bed when printing.

I printed the MainBase upside down with only a little support structure from the bed.

Changing my stock effector to this did not improve my print quality.
I found that lowering Jurk and Acceleration settings makes for a good stable printer.

There is no Z probe that will fit the printer if the big air directing part is installed.
I have found that Manual z probing works really well for me if you are interested I will add link below.

MANUAL Z PROBING FOR THE MICROMAKE D1 URL
https://github.com/Bougakov/Micromake-D1-3D-printer/blob/master/calibrating.md

I added a smaller air directing part more like the stock d1 version it will allow for a detachable z probe to mounted. I have created a z probe as well.

This a single string capo for the 5th string of a 5 strings bass (0.130 gauge), inspired by the fretlocks system (http://fretlocks.com). I use it to simulate a D string instead of a B string putting it in the 3rd fret. To make it work you need some biadhesive to keep the capo in place and always rember to remove it after playing to avoid damages on your fretboard by the tape glue.

If you need if for other strings gauges you can ask them to me OR edit my tinkercad project:
https://www.tinkercad.com/things/aHxEPFeuCDW-5th-string-bass-fret

To calculate the distances between the blocks use the pythagorean theorem, remember that string's gauge it's the diameter expressed in inches (example, 0.130 inches equal to 3,302 millimeters) and you need to have this value as diagolan distance between the blocks in order to fit the string.

The Star Topology

Description:
A star network comprises of multiple devices (Nodes) connected directly to the Router (Node)

Advantages:
it is very easy to install and is very easy to expand. It is suitable to LAN or WAN.

Disadvantages:
The main disadvantage of this topology is that if the server in the middle goes down then none of the nodes can connect anymore.

The Token Ring Topology

Description:
In the Token Ring Topology, every node is connected to each-other in such a way that they make a closed loop, within the closed loop a token which allows data to be sent travels through each node transporting data.

Advantages:
This type of network topology is very organized. Each node gets to send the data when it receives an empty token. This helps to reduces chances of collision. In a token ring topology all the traffic flows in one direction at a very high speed.

Disadvantages:
Each packet of data must pass through every single node between the source and destination. This makes it slower than a Star topology.

A mesh network uses each node to relay data within the network, a mesh network can be both wired and wireless.

Reflector Plate - single-sided copper pcb / galvanized steel sheet 23.3cm x 23.3cm

1. Print the antenna frame and six of the spacers.
  2. Cut a reflector plate to 23.3cm x 23.3cm.
  3. Align the antenna frame in the middle of the reflector plate and mark the center and the six spacer holes.
  4. Drill 3mm holes through each mark on the reflector plate (enlarge the center hole if needed so that the coax cable can pass through).
  5. Insert the coax cable through the back of the reflector plate.
  6. Remove 27mm of the coax cable outer sleeve.
  7. Fold back 8mm of the ground shield.
  8. Solder all of the exposed ground shield (keeping it straight).
  9. Solder the ground shield to the reflector plate.
  10. Trim 2mm from the inner conductor shield and tin with solder.
  11. Attach the spacers to the reflector plate using four M3x10mm button head screws.
  12. Insert 18 AWG silicon wire into the antenna frame, starting from the center wrap it right around through the channels.
  13. Solder the two ends of the wire together with 15mm of wire excess (this excess wire will be soldered to the coax ground shield later on).
  14. Attach the antenna frame to the spacers using six M3x10mm button head screws.
  15. Solder the joined antenna wire to the coax ground shield (be careful not to solder the inner conductor too).
  16. Perform a continuity check (test the coax fitting ground against the reflector plate and the antenna wire, make sure the coax inner conductor is not touching ground at this stage).
  17. Remove a small piece of the antenna wire silicon shield (directly opposite from the ground attachment) and solder the coax inner conductor to the exposed wire.

title: Makerbot MK8 1.75mm Filament all-Metal Bowden Extruder Wire feeder Ultimate Upgrade

description.text:
Filament guide and cylindrical insert for my upgrade of metal MK8 extruder from ebay.
Upgrade is created for bowden print - in my case for E3D Kraken.

My simple upgrade adds the power of the stepper motor and allows large retraction of the filament.

​I recently bought all-metal ​Makerbot ​MK8 bowden extruders - feeders - for my multihead printer .
After completing and plugging the stepper motor (which powered my old 3D printed extruder until now:​ https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1132201​) I found out that my 60NM stepper motor can not push the filament.

I realized that the stepper motor loses its strength due to the large diameter of the drive gear pulley (11mm).

First step is to replace the original gear pulley for a smaler gear pulley (9mm outside diameter and 7.5mm effective diameter in the groove for filament).

The next step is to replace the small pressure bearing for a large diameter 608ZZ bearing (small diameter of the bearing deforms filament and, in the case of use retractions, also tears it). Aluminum bearing attachment must be enlarged by grinding.

(for more informations search on www.instructables.com for: MK8 Metal Bowden Extruder Wire Feeder Ultimate Upgrade)
